<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 93 / International Company News: Savoy Pictures seeks share
listing after public issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LOS ANGELES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SAVOY PICTURES Entertainment, the recently formed US film production company
whose investors include the Pritzker family, Italy's Mr Silvio Berlusconi
and Carlton Communications of the UK, is planning to raise about Dollars 30m
by way of a public share offer aimed at quoting the company on the Nasdaq
over-the-counter stock market.
Proceeds of the share offer, which would be added to Savoy's current paid-in
capital of Dollars 165m, are expected to be used to help finance a roster of
more than a dozen movies that could establish Savoy as a new competitor
among the traditional Hollywood major studios.
Savoy is headed by Mr Victor Kaufman, who was president of Columbia Pictures
before it was acquired in 1989 by Sony of Japan.
Although formed only a year ago, the company is already on track to spend
about Dollars 250m a year producing and releasing feature movies.
An indication of the scale of Savoy's ambitions is the initial roster of
films underway. These include Mr Robert De Niro's debut as a director of A
Bronx Tale and films to be directed by Sir Richard Attenborough and Mr Mike
Nichols.
Savoy is also planning films to be produced in association with the
entertainment division of CBS Television and with Mr Ray Stark, the veteran
Hollywood producer. Savoy has already committed Dollars 46m to acquire film
projects.
Allen &amp; Company, the New York investment bank that owns about 9 per cent of
Savoy and is managing underwriter of the new share offer, has an option to
acquire more stock. The initial share offer would place about 12.5 per cent
of Savoy's equity on the stock market.
Savoy, which would have a market capitalisation of between Dollars 208m and
Dollars 240m after the share offer, is now 40 per cent owned by GHK
Investments, a limited partnership managed by Mr Jay Pritzker.
Carlton of the UK holds 9 per cent of Savoy while a further 6 per cent is
held by Home Box Office (HBO), the cable programming subsidiary of Time
Warner, the media and entertainment group. Mr Berlusconi is believed to have
about 5 per cent of the company.
</TEXT>
