<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 93 / International Company News: KOP losses more than doubled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KANSALLIS-Osake-Pankki, Finland's leading commercial bank, yesterday
disclosed a FM3.7bn (Dollars 651m) pre-tax loss for 1992 as credit losses
tripled and interest income shrank in the face of the severe domestic
recession. The loss is more than double the FM1.61bn deficit recorded in
1991.
The deterioration, which is symptomatic of the wider crisis in Finnish
banking, came with a warning that the bank would need to strengthen its
capital base this year because of the prospect of further losses.
KOP's interest income fell to FM14.7bn from FM16.2bn while profit from
financial operations dropped 12.7 per cent to FM2.62bn. At the same time,
credit losses tripled to FM4.27bn from FM1.34bn, mainly because of problems
in the corporate sector, while non-performing loans, after write-offs,
soared 41.7 per cent to FM7.1bn, or 7.7 per cent of total lending.
'Soaring interest rates, the collapse of asset values, company failures and
growing unemployment caused serious problems,' said Mr Pertti Voutilainen,
KOP chairman and chief executive. 'Net interest income shrank as a result of
forgone interest income, and lending write-offs saw explosive growth.'
Internal rationalisation, including an 8 per cent cut in staff numbers to
8,500 and a 2 per cent fall in non-interest expenses, was unable to stem the
negative tide.
One bright spot was an 84 per cent increase in non-interest income to
FM1.98bn as a result of successful foreign exchange dealing. This helped to
lift total group income to FM4.60bn from FM4.08bn.
The bank's figures did not include the results of STS-Bank, with which KOP
has recently merged. Non-performing loans at STS amounted to FM2.6bn,
although much of that should be shouldered by the government's guarantee
fund.
KOP said it had started investigating ways of strengthening its capital
base, either through a rights issue or through support from the government
or a combination of both. The bank's international capital adequacy ratio at
the year-end was 9.13 per cent, but this will fall towards 8 per cent during
1993 in the face of further losses. The bank is expected to remain in the
red in both 1993 and 1994.
</TEXT>
