<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 93 / International Company News: Gloom settles over Finnish banks
 -Christopher Brown-Humes reports as the sector is hit by recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KANSALLIS-Osake-Pankki, Finland's leading commercial bank, yesterday
inaugurated what will probably be the gloomiest reporting season in Finnish
banking history.
Unitas, the country's number two bank, is expected to reveal a loss of at
least FM3bn (Dollars 528m), after a FM128m profit in 1991, and even bigger
deficits could be reported by Skopbank and the Savings Bank of Finland, both
of which are now under state control. Losses for the whole sector will
amount to FM15bn-FM20bn, more than twice the 1991 level, with non-performing
loans estimated at a staggering FM80bn.
At the heart of the crisis lies the severe Finnish recession, exacerbated by
high real interest rates, which have brought share and property values down
sharply in the past three years and pushed many small and medium-sized
companies into bankruptcy. Credit losses and non-performing loans have
soared.
True, interest rates have come down during the autumn, improving the banks'
margins and share prices have risen strongly since October. But there has
been no let up in the pace of bankruptcies and the amount of non-performing
loans has risen.
The scale of the difficulties has meant that even the extensive
rationalisation measures and major staff reduction programmes being carried
out by many of the banks have made little impact.
'The amount of bad loans is more than the equity of most of the banks. The
value of their shares depends on the extent to which the government is
prepared to help them out,' says Mr Jari Eklund, analyst with KOP Investment
Research.
What made yesterday's KOP statement particularly gloomy was the assessment
that it will take years for the banking system's problems to be resolved.
'Normal levels of profitability will hardly be reached until the late
1990s,' said Mr Pertti Voutilainen, KOP chairman and chief executive. He has
already indicated that KOP is unlikely to return to profit before 1995.
This year the slump in the domestic market will continue, despite the
improved outlook for exports, and it is by no means certain that GNP, which
has fallen 10 per cent in the past two years, will be positive. The problems
in the corporate sector will continue, particularly for companies exposed to
the devaluation of the Finnish markka such as importing companies or those
with big foreign currency loans. At the same time, greater difficulties are
expected in the household sector, with Finnish unemployment now at a record
18.6% level.
Many people in the industry suspect the government may have to offer even
more financial help than it has indicated so far. Last's year FM20bn
guarantee fund has been severely depleted and FM8bn in preference capital
fully utilised. Last week parliament approved a further FM20bn in assistance
for the banks in 1993, and there has been talk of a further FM10bn being
made available in due course.
The best that can be hoped is that things will not get any worse. But for
the banking sector to start pulling out of the crisis, there has to be a
broader economic recovery. Fortunately there are positive signs, including
rising exports and the recent decision by the Bank of Finland to cut base
rates to 7.5 per cent.
In the meantime one of the government's main priorities will be resolving
the future of the Savings Bank of Finland and Skopbank, the central bank of
the savings banks.
Last year Unitas pulled out of talks which might have led to it merging with
both these ailing groups. Then, several weeks ago, KOP revealed that it had
made contact with the state about a possible merger with them.
This news has alarmed the rest of the banking sector, partly because a
combination of the three banks would give KOP an estimated 40 per cent share
of the overall market. The other banks also say the move would distort
competition, if it was effected with the aid of non-repayable state support.
They believe a fairer solution would be for the healthy parts of the two
groups to be divided among all of them, with the bad loans being hived off
into a separate unit.
It is not just a question of Skopbank and the Savings Bank of Finland being
helped out. KOP has already indicated it will almost certainly need a
capital injection this year, and may well need direct support from the
government to prevent its capital adequacy falling below statutory minimums.
By contrast, Unitas shows every sign of wanting to pull through its
difficulties without government support - but it will want to be sure that
its competitive position is not endangered in the process.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FiZnland, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P602  Commercial Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>IND  Industry profile.
</TP>
