<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 93 / UK Company News: John Menzies shows sharp improvement to
Pounds 3.8m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Menzies, chairman of the Edinburgh-based retail and wholesale group
which bears his name, said the company had 'produced a result which is
satisfactory within the overall economic environment' when it revealed a
jump in pre-tax profits from Pounds 2.1m to Pounds 3.8m in the six months to
October 31.
The shares rose 16p to 482p.
In August, the Monopolies and Mergers Commission initiated an investigation
 -scheduled to be completed by July - into the wholesale distribution of
newspapers in England and Wales, territories where, according to Mr Ranald
Noel-Paton, group managing director, Menzies has a market share of about
16.5 per cent.
He said he was confident of a 'favourable outcome', stressing that the MMC's
brief was for newspapers only, not magazines and periodicals, and did not
cover Scotland, where Menzies is strong. Its UK market share is about 20 per
cent.
On the distribution side, Mr Noel-Paton said that turnover at John Menzies
Wholesale rose 12 per cent.
TBD, now including Hammick's book wholesale division since the sale of the
Hammick's retail bookshop chain, saw turnover fall, partly because of the
drop in consumer demand for recorded music. Mr Noel-Paton said this was a
recessionary downturn, but also influenced by the impact of video games and
a lack of availability of good new product - 'it's hard to get too excited
by the latest compilation of Abba hits'.
Turnover at Universal Office Supplies was up 12 per cent 'in a flat market',
and 20 per cent when RMG, acquired for about Pounds 2.5m from Waverley
Cameron in August, was included.
The 274-strong John Menzies retail chain was 'resilient' with turnover 'flat
in real terms', though it traded below budget.
The 171 Early Learning Centres in the UK achieved a 10 per cent turnover
rise 'with no erosion of margin'. Apart from the small wholesale business
which was sold to its management, Early Learning Inc, the US operation, will
be completely closed by the end of February. Mr Noel-Paton said: 'We did
everything possible to effect a sale and led a lot of horses to water, but
none of them drank.'
Group turnover grew to Pounds 531.9m (Pounds 489.3m) and interest charges
fell Pounds 800,000 to Pounds 1.6m. Earnings emerged at 2.9p (0.9p) per
share and the interim dividend is lifted to 3.8p (3.6p).
</TEXT>
