<PROFILE>_AN-DBICOAASFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930209
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 93 / UK Company News: Peter Black rises 27% on back of interest
cost cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REDUCED interest costs and improved margins lay behind a 27 per cent advance
in interim pre-tax profit at Peter Black Holdings, the personal care and
footwear group.
The share price rose 14p to close at 180p, its highest level for four years.
The pre-tax profit increase from Pounds 4.52m to Pounds 5.73m was struck on
flat turnover of Pounds 61.1m (Pounds 60.5m) in the six months to November
28. Nearly two thirds of sales are to Marks and Spencer. Operating profit
rose nearly 7 per cent to Pounds 6.15m (Pounds 5.76m).
Interest costs were cut from Pounds 1.24m to Pounds 419,000. Mr Stephen
Lister, finance director, said internal cash generation had reduced net debt
to Pounds 3.6m - gearing of 9 per cent - compared with Pounds 10.5m in
November 1991.
In the personal care division, like-for-like turnover was flat at Pounds 21m
(Pounds 22m) after allowing for a small disposal. Pre-tax profit rose to
Pounds 2.65m (Pounds 2m).
Mr Gordon Black, joint chairman whose family controls 39 per cent of the
equity, said sales of toiletries and gifts were satisfactory, but the
cosmetics market remained difficult. Benefits flowed through from the
concentration of production on one site instead of two, a move made in late
1991.
At English Grains, the own-label business had done better than the brands.
The company made about 1.5bn pills a year, with vitamins as the biggest
sellers, and capacity was being increased.
In footwear and accessories, pre-tax profit grew to Pounds 2.23m (Pounds
1.75m) on turnover of Pounds 33.1m (Pounds 31.8m). Sales rose at Newbold,
which makes fashion shoes for M and S and other retailers, and in the import
business. At the Keighley footwear and accessories subsidiary, profit
improvement came from enhanced efficiency.
Distribution - which encompasses contracts for more than 30 companies - and
leisure/retail at Hornsea Freeport together increased profits to Pounds
845,000 (Pounds 762,000) on sales of Pounds 7m (Pounds 6.69m).
Earnings per share rose to 7.05p (5.56p) and the interim dividend goes up to
0.93p (0.77p).
COMMENT
Peter Black's revival has been given a fair wind by the resilient M and S,
but the management also played its hand well. Signs of this are the
financial discipline that has led to debt and stock reduction, rationalised
production and expansion of third party distribution. Within the M and S
circle Black is serving areas of potential in women's shoes and cosmetics.
Outside it, progress continues to be made in sales to other retailers. With
profit growth restored on sluggish turnover, a significant increase in
demand would have a rapid impact on the bottom line. With profits weighted
towards the first half, a full-year figure of Pounds 8.3m (Pounds 6.6m) is
forecast, giving a p/e of 17.5. The share price has shot up by nearly three
quarters in less than three months and so the bargain days are gone. It
remains worth holding.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Peter Black Holdings.
</CO>
<XX>
