<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 93 / The Lex Column: Eurotunnel
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Rather like Mr Norman Lamont, Eurotunnel's Sir Alastair Morton must be
wearying of huge borrowing requirements, fierce political skirmishes and
staring down long dark holes. But Sir Alastair can at least see some light
at the end of the tunnel. Yesterday's encouraging - if tentative - news of
progress towards resolution of its dispute with its contractors lifted
Eurotunnel's shares by almost 3 per cent. The sterling units have risen
nearly 50 per cent since mid-December. Although aided by currency movements,
the rise appears to reflect a shift in investor perceptions. Eurotunnel has
begun its evolution from unpredictable construction project to more
dependable transport utility.
Assuming the bitter wrangle with contractors can be resolved satisfactorily,
Eurotunnel should be able to complete the project within the year. TV shots
of trains carrying beaming passengers will help sentiment, if the opening
itself does little to alleviate the project's pressing financial needs.
Eurotunnel will probably still require more equity, but the pressure is
easing. With about 70 per cent of its debt at floating rates, Eurotunnel
will benefit if interest rates remain low in the UK and start falling in
France.
Once construction and refinancing are complete, investors should be able to
look forward to a predictable income stream. But everything depends on
traffic volumes. It is not yet clear what sort of price war rival operators
have in mind. The UK government has yet to agree on a high-speed rail link
to London and dividends are many years away.
</TEXT>
