<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / European group may seek radio licence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLT, the Luxembourg-based international broadcasting group, has renewed its
interest in investing in UK radio and television, and is examining the
London commercial radio frequencies to be advertised next month.
Mr Gaston Thorn, president of CLT and former president of the European
Commission, was in London last week to express his interest to Lord
Chalfont, chairman of the Radio Authority, which regulates commercial radio.
The frequencies to be advertised include those used by LBC, Melody, Jazz and
Spectrum radios.
CLT is interested in setting up a music-based station in the south of
England and would like to repeat the success of its Atlantic 252, which
broadcasts mainly to the north and Midlands. Atlantic broadcasts pop music
and has a weekly audience of 4.25m adults, according to Radio Joint Audience
Research.
It is unlikely that CLT would be granted a London licence to broadcast just
pop music. The radio authority has a responsibility to broaden choice in the
area and Capital, whose licence will not be re-advertised until next year,
is a well-established pop station.
Mr Thorn says CLT is also interested in television. It would like to take a
minority stake in an ITV company, and then look at joint ventures in
continental Europe.
</TEXT>
