<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / Greek Cypriots go to polls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NICOSIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GREEK Cypriot voters gave Mr George Vassiliou, the incumbent, a commanding
lead of 7.5 percentage points in yesterday's first round of the Cyprus
presidential election.
Mr Vassiliou, an independent backed by the island's powerful Communist
party, did better than expected, winning 44.2 per cent of the vote to 36.7
per cent for his right-wing opponent, Mr Glascos Clerides.
Mr Paschalis Paschalides, a political newcomer supported by the centre-right
Diko party and the Socialists, finished a poor third with 18.6 per cent.
Mr Vassiliou is now favourite to win a second five-year term in next
Sunday's run-off ballot against Mr Clerides.
The vote is widely seen as a referendum on the latest United Nations
proposals for reuniting the Greek and Turkish communities on Cyprus. Mr
Vassiliou has played an active role in developing the UN 'set of ideas',
which proposes a settlement based on a federated state with Greek and
Turkish Cypriots living in separate zones.
Mr Vassiliou said the election results indicated that there was strong
Greek-Cypriot backing for his efforts 'to exploit the favourable
international climate, to increase the pressure on Turkey and to reach a
just and viable solution' of the Cyprus problem. The island has been
partitioned since 1974, when Turkish troops took over northern Cyprus in
response to an Athens-led coup aimed at uniting the island with Greece.
Mr Clerides is expected to seek an alliance with Diko ahead of the second
ballot, offering prominent centrists cabinet positions in return for their
party's support.
