<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A group of some of South Africa's less charming citizens is the subject of
Cutting Edge's investigation, Soweto Flying Squad (C4, 9.00). Here is the
stuff of late-20th century heroics. The squad is made up of young men,
single, white, and heavily armed. They patrol the violent streets of Soweto,
shooting and being shot, in a nightmarish world of urban violence in which
the niceties of legal procedure can have no place.
The advance of capitalism in China, partly overt and partly by stealth, is
the subject of two films in tonight's edition of South (C4, 11.00), the
documentary series which screens the work of film-makers from the southern
hemisphere. A film about Hong Kong focuses on the powerful alliance between
leading figures in the colony's business life and the Communist hierarchy on
the mainland, and the problems this poses for governor Chris Patten.
Does Robert Redford, now pushing 60, still deserve to be called one of the
best-looking men in the world? In Film 93 Special (BBC 1, 10.10) he talks to
Barry Norman.
</TEXT>
