<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / Nervous end to roller-coaster ride: The uncertain future
facing the railway supply industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER A 120-year roller-coaster ride through the peaks and troughs of
equipment contracting, Britain's railway supply industry is facing an
uncertain future.
Domestic orders are drying up, and the controversial privatisation of
British Rail is looming - last week the government named seven sections of
BR that could be in private sector hands by the end of next year.
On top of that - and in spite of a likely go-ahead for the Pounds 300m
Heathrow Express - there is continuing uncertainty over money-spinning
'mega-projects' such as London Underground's Pounds 1.7bn Jubilee Line
extension and the Pounds 2.5bn Channel tunnel rail link.
The industry has reached a critical point. At stake are more than 60
companies with combined annual turnover of about Pounds 1.75bn, although the
top 20 companies account for Pounds 1.2bn of the sales.
Some of those companies are giants of the European engineering scene such as
GEC Alsthom and Asea Brown Boveri. Yet all are feeling the effects of the
current squeeze.
'If we don't get an order in the UK in the next six months, we'll not be
here by the end of 1994,' says Mr Graham Bradburn, commercial director at
Birmingham-based Hunslet Transportation Projects, a big producer of
passenger rail vehicles.
According to Mr David Gillan, director of the Railway Industry Association,
the equipment suppliers' trade body, privatisation puts about half the
industry's 30,000 jobs at risk immediately, and all of them in the long
term. For every employee in rail contracting there is another in industries
that are only partly dependent on rail business, supplying everything from
seats and carpets to nuts and bolts.
Yet, in a year when investment by British Rail has reached a record Pounds
1.6bn and London Underground spending is at comparatively high levels, are
things really as bad as industry leaders say?
Certainly, few rail equipment suppliers could have predicted their
predicament three years ago. After many years of relatively low domestic
demand, a considerable number of orders were placed in the late 1980s, with
the promise of more to come. The industry responded by expanding and
modernising its production facilities to enable it to meet projected demand.
At least a third of this year's spending by BR is related to Channel tunnel
business, but that is now declining.
The combined effects of the recession, which has dented BR's revenues, and
delays over the Channel tunnel rail link and other projects mean that some
suppliers will face serious declines in orders by the end of the year.
The increases in BR's external financing limit announced in the Autumn
Statement will not benefit suppliers, says Mr Gillan. 'It's new money for BR
but it will go to further subsidise loss-making services.'
As a result, a number of large contractors could run out of work by the
middle of next year, with smaller sub-contractors feeling the pinch even
earlier.
'There is a mistaken belief in the minds of ministers that a short gap in
production is sustainable,' says Mr Gillan. 'But shareholders don't allow
production capacity to be kept open against the possibility of getting
business.'
Then comes privatisation. The very people who ought to be planning rail
projects do not know where they are going to be in two years, says Mr
Gillan. A break in ordering is therefore inevitable.
Mr Bradburn at Austrian-owned Hunslet TPL says that any incoming private
franchisee will not be buying rolling stock until it knows what its
operating costs are, which could take two years.
He doubts, too, whether franchisees will be keen to lease rolling stock
unless they receive guarantees on issues such as residual values - the value
of equipment at the end of a lease. The government is allowing BR to lease
up to Pounds 150m of rolling stock in the next three years to create a
leasing market in the run-up to privatisation.
Perhaps the best hope for the industry is if the government ties the award
of franchises to spending on rolling stock and infrastructure, a possibility
that Mr Roger Freeman, minister for public transport, has not ruled out.
But the question remains whether suppliers can make it through the next two
years and on to the mid 1990s and the next century, when some of the
projects under discussion or delayed may at last take place.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>UnZited Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
