<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / 'Yobs' blow loud Euro-raspberry at Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YOUNG Conservatives yesterday looked to the mainland of Europe from the
seaside resort of Southend and, to the embarrassment of their elders, blew
an enormous raspberry at Mr John Major's policy on Europe.
By a large majority of hands and even more foot-stomping, they rejected a
motion that reflected the prime minister's policy. It said Britain's best
interests would be served 'by playing an active role in the development of
the European Community'.
Sir Edward Heath, the former prime minister and YC life patron, was booed
and hissed, and his likening of young Euro-rebels to yobs was turned back on
him. 'If I'm a football hooligan then at least when I go to the Continent I
fight for Britain,' said Mr Matthew Palmer of London Young Conservatives.
The young Tories, after a few years' good behaviour for the general
election, were back on form.
'It is a peculiar culture,' said one cabinet minister, leaving the
conference after making his speech. Most of the big-name speakers stayed
little more than a few hours; Sir Norman Fowler, Conservative party
chairman, left soon after lunch on Saturday.
In the late 1980s the battles were between Heathite 'wets' and Thatcherite
'drys'. Now, reduced in numbers, they refight the 1990 Tory leadership
battle. Baroness Thatcher is cheered on every mention, Mr Michael Heseltine,
the trade and industry secretary who brought her down, is jeered.
Perhaps to his embarrassment, Mr Peter Lilley, the rightwing social security
secretary, received the best reception. Part of his speech was on economic
policy since Black Wednesday. He got only as far as 'since we left the ERM .
. . ' before the cheering started. If he wanted to smile, Mr Lilley hid his
emotions beautifully.
The Europe debate saw copies of the Maastricht treaty torn up, and
government loyalists shouted down. 'Maastricht is a good deal for Britain
and we should jump at the chance to ratify it,' began one speaker to shouts
of 'lies'. 'Only joking,' he added quickly.
The hunched figure of Sir Teddy Taylor, local MP and leading Euro-sceptic,
sat at the front. Afterwards he quoted 'that rather strange singer' Bob
Marley, urging his young friends to 'stand up for your rights and keep
fighting'.
The conference slogan, 'Young Conservatives, the next generation', adapted
the sub-title of Star Trek's new series. Mr Major may sometimes wish he can
beam them into space.
</TEXT>
