<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / Boost for leading pension managers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRONG performances by two leading fund management houses last year are
likely to lead to further concentration of the management of Britain's
occupational pension funds.
Preliminary data shows that Gartmore and Phillips &amp; Drew Fund Management
(PDFM) outperformed the median rate of return by at least 5 and 3 percentage
points respectively.
The other two of the biggest four active managers, Mercury and Schroder, are
believed to have been some way behind but still close to the average.
Gartmore, which now manages pension funds worth Pounds 10.5bn, after adding
Pounds 1.8bn in new business last year, claims a median rate of return of
25.8 per cent for its client funds. Its pooled fund, Gartmore Long-Term
Balanced, a unitised fund used by certain smaller clients, returned 29 per
cent.
A performance measurement company called Caps estimates that the median
pension fund return in 1992 was 20.6 per cent, although this may be revised
when more results are filed.
According to Mr David Watts, head of pension funds at Gartmore, it was 'a
most remarkable year' in which the managers added value in every area.
The main elements included a heavy overseas exposure and, within that, an
emphasis on dollar assets, which paid off handsomely in the final quarter.
At PDFM, which manages about twice as much pension fund money as Gartmore,
there was a good performance in UK equities and a profitable exposure to
French bonds, said Mr Tony Dye, the company's investment strategist. But
risks were reduced by a high (10 per cent to 11 per cent) investment in
index-linked gilt-edged stock.
Consultants say there was an unusually large spread between the best and the
worst results last year. One fund with two management companies found there
was a 9 per cent gap in performance between them.
Pension fund management has become highly competitive and in recent years
contracts have been gravitating towards a handful of successful investment
houses. According to a consultant: 'These results will intensify the move
towards the majors.'
But it is performance over several years rather than a single year that
counts. 'We are having to spend our time dampening down our clients'
expectations,' said Mr Watts.
Caps has published performance figures for the pooled funds of about 60
investment institutions, which also show a wide range of investment
performance.
