<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / Revenue accounts proposals attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INLAND REVENUE proposals to require self-employed people to prepare their
accounts for the tax year ending in April would place 'impossible pressures'
on accountants, the Chartered Association of Certified Accountants warned
today, Andrew Jack writes.
At the moment a range of deadlines is available for the self-employed. In
response to the Revenue's consultative document on restructuring the tax
system issued late last year, the association argues against the case for
'fiscal accounting'. It says accounts preparation for the self-employed
would be compressed into a six-month period that is already taken up with
pay-as-you-earn tax work. That would force businesses to recruit temporary
staff, and threaten to jeopardise the quality of tax preparation work
carried out.
The association also says that the proposals shift the administrative burden
on to the taxpayer, and could lead to the creation of a more adversarial
system.
</TEXT>
