<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / Vauxhall acts to reduce stocks held by dealers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VAUXHALL IS introducing a new car distribution system intended to reduce
stocks held at dealers' premises and cut the total number of vehicles in its
supply pipeline by 20 per cent.
When fully implemented by 1995, it is expected to save the company and its
dealers 'tens of millions of pounds a year', according to Mr Dean Barrett,
marketing services director of the General Motors subsidiary.
More than half of all new Vauxhalls sold are transferred between dealerships
to satisfy customer orders, rather than supplied directly to the dealer by
Vauxhall.
In future Vauxhall's 535 dealers will draw their cars from a network of five
large storage facilities, each linked strategically to either a Vauxhall
manufacturing plant or, in the case of imported vehicles, their port of
entry.
The system bears some similarities to that already instituted at rival Rover
Group, which last autumn opened a network of seven wholly owned regional
distribution centres.
As with the Vauxhall system, Rover's dealers carry only showroom stock and
test vehicles. They no longer carry bulk stocks in their compounds but call
up cars as they are ordered from the seven regional centres.
Rover, which has smaller UK sales than Vauxhall, believes its own system
could save the group and its dealers up to Pounds 80m a year.
Traditionally, Vauxhall's dealers have held six weeks' or more of stocks,
swapping them as necessary as orders for a particular specification and
colour came in.
The new system is scheduled to start in the spring.
</TEXT>
