<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / BA and Virgin likely to renew talks today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Airways and Virgin Atlantic are likely today to renew talks in
London aimed at striking a peace deal in the wake of BA's 'dirty tricks'
campaign against its rival.
Virgin said yesterday that it wanted successful dis-cussions with BA but
that it still intended to take action against BA if a deal was not agreed
this week.
Sir Colin Marshall, BA's executive chairman, said he wanted the talks to end
amicably and 'the sooner the better'.
Without a deal, Virgin threatens to begin anti-trust action in the US, as
well as alleging to the European Commission that BA has abused its dominant
market position. Virgin also might instigate court action under the Data
Protection Act or pursue claims of breach of copyright.
In three meetings held so far between the two sides, Virgin has claimed that
BA's activities inflicted upon it serious commercial damage running into
tens of millions of pounds.
Virgin has not publicly specified its demands, although it is understood to
have tabled a series of proposals. These range from cash compensation to the
use of BA aircraft-servicing facilities.
The allocation of take-off and landing 'slots' at London's Heathrow airport
is also thought to be on the agenda.
Although it is understood that some progress towards agreement has been
made, there is some surprise in the Virgin camp at the time the talks are
taking, and it appears determined not to see them drag on beyond this week.
Virgin is being represented by Mr Sid Pennington, managing director of
Virgin Atlantic, and Mr Trevor Abbott, financial adviser to Mr Richard
Branson, Virgin's chairman. Mr Robert Ayling, who on Friday was appointed
BA's group managing director, is representing BA.
If a deal is reached, it is likely that Mr Branson, will meet Sir Colin to
complete an agreement. Meanwhile, fall-out from Lord King's announcement
last friday that he would retire early from the post of BA chairman
continued over the weekend.
Lord Hanson, chairman of Hanson, the industrial conglomerate, and a friend
of Lord King, criticised some of the airline's non-executive directors for
failing to fully support the chairman during the aftermath of the 'dirty
tricks' affair. The suggestion was refuted both by Sir Colin and by Lord
King. Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary, said he would have
sacked the people involved in the 'dirty tricks' affair if he had been in
the government and BA had been a state-owned company.
'I think it is quite deplorable and a disgrace,' he said. 'The BA board is a
bit like the Tory cabinet - doesn't anyone resign any more when you get
caught out?'
</TEXT>
