<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / AEEU hopeful on single-union deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE number of single-union agreements will increase if the electricians'
wing of the Amalagmated Engineering and Electrical Union rejoins the Trades
Union Congress in the autumn, according to AEEU leaders.
The leadership today launches its campaign to convince the union's 600,000
members to vote in favour of rejoining the TUC. A postal ballot will be held
next month.
Mr Paul Gallagher, general secretary of the electricians' section, says that
returning to the TUC after being expelled for defying rules five years ago
will provide 'great opportunities to negotiate more single-union
agreements'.
His union was at the forefront of the trend to single-union agreements that
peaked in the late 1980s. In forthcoming research to be published in the
Industrial Relations Journal, Mr Gregor Gall, a research student at
Manchester School of Management, says the old EETPU signed 66 of the 194
single-union deals he has found, followed by the engineering union with a
further 57 of them.
Mr Gall points out that 93 of the total deals were made between 1986 and
1989 with the largest number of 37 achieved in 1988. Only 14 more have been
signed since 1990. He argues that the sharp decline in such agreements after
1990 was mainly due to the recession and fall in new overseas investment,
particularly by Japanese companies who were at the forefront of the earlier
single-union deal wave.
But he argues an important secondary cause for the drop in interest in them
over the past four years stemmed from employer concern that signing new
style deals solely with the EETPU would destabilise their industrial
relations once the union was outside the TUC.
In a survey of 37 single-union agreements just published by Industrial
Relations Services it was found management favoured such deals because it
ensured they could achieve 'high levels of flexibility in the use of
labour'.
As many as 73 per cent of the companies surveyed said they had introduced
team-working as a result of having single-union agreements while 65 per cent
had 'adopted multi-skilling, where employees are required to undertake a
wide range of tasks without demarcation of any kind'.
Just over half reported they had introduced just-in-time production methods
and 62 per cent they operated total quality control.
The research also found that single-union deals brought single status for
workers in three quarters of the agreements, breaking down the old blue and
white-collar worker distinctions in terms and conditions of employment.
Joint consultation committees are also a feature of most single-union deals.
</TEXT>
