<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / Single Market Watch: Expectant hush in barrier-free
Community - Information is awaited on its progress
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT is just over a month since the European Community abolished most of its
internal barriers to free movement of goods, people, capital and services,
and the single market is quiet - too quiet. 'At the moment it is a kingdom
of silence, but there will come a point when we will be overwhelmed by good
or maybe bad news,' said Mr Raniero Vanni d'Archirafi, the new internal
market commissioner, last week.
Mr Vanni d'Archirafi meets EC internal market ministers today in Brussels,
for the first time since the Community passed its January 1 deadline for a
barrier-free Europe. Everyone will be asking each other the same question:
how is it going? In theory, the proposed legislative work is almost done. Of
the 282 measures in the original 1985 single market programme, only 18 have
not been agreed. At the end of last month, member states had transferred an
average 72 per cent of the adopted measures into national law.
In practice, it is hard to tell how the market is working. Specific
complaints, particularly about continuing passport checks at internal
borders, have been notified to Brussels. But national officials responsible
for the single market had their first 'consultative' meeting last Tuesday
and concluded no evidence existed that free circulation of goods, services
and capital was being impeded.
That said, Mr Vanni d'Archirafi, 61, seeks to dispel the idea Brussels will
be pursuing a hands-off policy to the single market in the first half of
this year. A former senior Italian diplomat, he was clearly taken aback by
reaction to his first press conference last month, when he suggested an
'armistice or truce' on the single market.
His comments gave the impression there would be a three or four-month 'grace
period' in which the Commission would turn a blind eye to infringements of
the market's new rules, and even ignore governments which dragged their feet
on implementation of single market directives. As such, his stance was
roundly criticised by the European business community, relying on the
Commission to ensure governments transpose EC directives into national law
and enforce them.
But as he explained last week, this was not the signal he wanted to send.
'As far as transposition is concerned there will be no mercy.' The
commissioner says the first months of the market will be spent gathering
information, preparing a 'master plan' for enacting some of last year's
Sutherland committee recommendations on how to make the single market work.
The real test comes when genuine cross-border complaints start to feed back
through the EC network. Mr Peter Sutherland, the former commissioner who
headed the committee on implementation of the market, has warned member
states may try to abuse the principle of subsidiarity, by claiming that in
certain areas of the single market Brussels is tinkering with the
responsibilities of national governments.
Mr Vanni d'Archirafi says Brussels will have no hesitation in following up
abuse of market rules. 'The Commission has to be guardian of the
construction (of the single market), here I'm referring to transposition of
directives in particular. The goal is not to be deliberately soft or strict;
the goal is to make sure the single market works.'
National representatives are trying to consolidate a network of contact
points to help people transmit difficulties with the new area of free
movement to the relevant authorities. Only when it comes to passport checks
is the new commissioner likely to be more cautious. He is sympathetic to the
problems member states have with lifting controls on travellers within the
EC, especially at airports, pointing out that architects of the single
market never forecast the increase in immigration from eastern Europe.
He wants to persuade member states to meet 'deadlines' of the end of June
for scrapping all controls on internal land borders, and the end of December
for ports and airports. As for Britain, which wants to retain passport
checks, he says: 'I will try not to let the division (between the UK and
continental member states) become greater.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>European Commission (EC).
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>EuZropean Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
<XX>
People:-
</XX>
<PE>Raniero Vanni d'Archirafi, New Internal Market Commissioner
    European Commission (EC).
</PE>
