<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 93 / Whitehall fails to keep its numbers in check
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROGRESS Mrs Margaret (now Baroness) Thatcher made in cutting the number
of civil servants is being reversed under Mr John Major. The total is rising
again, despite the search for public expenditure cuts.
There were more than 565,000 civil servants in April 1992, according to
recently released Treasury statistics, a net increase of almost 11,500 on
the previous year.
While the number of white-collar civil servants rose by more than 14,000 the
overall increase in the Civil Service was slightly less because of
continuing cuts among blue-collar civil servants, whose numbers have been
halved since 1984. The overall white-collar figure has returned to the 1984
level of 500,000.
Mrs Ann Robinson, head of the policy unit at the Institute of Directors,
said the figures reflected the government's failure to get to grips with the
size of the public services payroll.
'If the chancellor is going to reduce public spending to curb the budget
deficit, he has no alternative but to look at the number of people employed
in the public services,' she said.
While some departments such as Trade and Industry have cut white-collar
payrolls, others such as the Home Office and Social Security Department have
grown.
A variety of reasons is given for the growth:
The Lord Chancellor's Department, with a 17 per cent increase in its
white-collar payroll since the start of 1980, blames a heavier civil and
criminal justice workload.
The Home Office, which has increased white-collar staff from under 30,000 to
more than 46,000 in the same period, cites prison service expansion and
increasing immigration work.
The rapid increase in unemployment in the past two years has fuelled a 27
per cent jump in the number of civil servants in the Employment Service.
The executive agencies which are supposed to impose business disciplines on
government services are responsible for much of the increase in the number
of civil servants. Of the 28 oldest agencies, 21 have increased staff totals
since inception.
Pumping up numbers, Page 6
</TEXT>
