FT  08 FEB 93 / International Company News: Bell Canada seeks rate rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STIFFENING competition in Canada's telephone market has led Bell Canada, the
country's biggest phone company, to apply for the first rise in basic local
rates for 10 years, writes Bernard Simon in Toronto.
Bell, which has a monopoly on local services in the key markets of Ontario
and Quebec, said the increase is required to make up for a gradual erosion
of income from long-distance services.
The proposed increase would average 10 per cent for households and 9 per
cent for business customers. It must still be approved by a federal
regulatory agency.
Bell's lucrative long-distance business provided a CDollars 1.9bn (USDollars
1.49bn) subsidy to local services last year. According to Bell, the fee for
residential services currently averages CDollars 10 a month, compared with a
cost to the company of CDollars 40. The fee covers an unlimited number of
local calls.
